summary:
Niacin (Vitamin B3) is the only vitamin among the listed ones that can be synthesized in vivo by humans through the enzymatic conversion of tryptophan via the kynurenine pathway. Unlike other vitamins such as folate, pantothenic acid, and cobalamins—which depend exclusively on dietary or bacterial sources—the partial metabolic production of niacin occurs directly within the human body. 

(Note: Despite claims about microbial origin for B12, its actual synthesis happens outside the human body.)

(End summary)

We are asked to summarize Agent1’s reasoning regarding which vitamin is synthesized in vivo by humans.

Key clinical facts identified:

- No vitamin is fully synthesized de novo by humans;
- Among all listed vitamins, **niacin (B3)** undergoes **endogenous formation**: converted from dietary tryptophan using enzymes like IDO and KMO along the kynurenine pathway;
- Other vitamins either originate purely from food (**pantothenic acid**) or are produced by intestinal bacteria before consumption (**cobalamin/B12**);
- Since niacin has documented pathways enabling limited but real internal synthesis, it meets criteria more than any other option;

Conclusion drawn: Although incomplete compared to complete synthetic metabolism seen elsewhere, **niacin represents the closest match clinically defined as 'being synthesized' due to proven in-body transformation from nutrient precursors**.

Only one vitamin fits strictly enough: niacin.

